{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496920"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:59:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:59:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1437"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1437"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.02,0.77,0.06,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1437"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101533"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1437"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1437"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83972"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"987"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1887"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"},{"type":"tags","id":"2097"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8067"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8086"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15556"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33807"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42320"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43844"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101533"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of progressive fatigue, weakness, and paraesthesia in his hands and feet. He reports difficulty with his normal daily activities and occasional episodes of lightheadedness. His medical history includes hypertension, osteoarthritis and a Roux-en-Y gastric bypass performed three years ago for management of obesity. He does not take any regular medications and consumes six standard drinks a week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 135/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.9\u00b0C. He has pale conjunctiva and glossitis. There is a mild, diffuse neck swelling. Cardiovascular and respiratory examinations are unremarkable. Neurological examination reveals reduced proprioception and vibration sense in the lower limbs, with diminished ankle reflexes bilaterally. Romberg\u0027s test is positive. His gait is wide-based and ataxic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 115 g/L (135-175)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean corpuscular volume: 110 fL (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 4.5 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet count: 150 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (150-400).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying pathophysiological mechanism for this patient\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inadequate dietary folate intake","Autoimmune destruction of pancreatic beta cells","Intrinsic factor deficiency leading to malabsorption","Excessive alcohol consumption","Iodine deficiency causing thyroid dysfunction"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s history of bariatric surgery, combined with his neurological symptoms (paraesthesia, proprioception and vibration sense deficits, positive Romberg\u0027s test, and ataxic gait) suggest subacute combined degeneration of the spinal cord, a complication of B12 deficiency. The macrocytic anaemia (elevated MCV) further support this diagnosis. This can occur following Roux-en-Y gastric bypass surgery due to reduced intrinsic factor production in the bypassed stomach. The underlying pathophysiological mechanism for vitamin B12 deficiency in these cases is \u003Cstrong\u003Eintrinsic factor deficiency leading to malabsorption\u003C/strong\u003E of vitamin B12.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInadequate dietary folate intake\u003C/strong\u003E can cause macrocytic anaemia, but it does not explain the neurological findings seen here, nor is it a common complication after bariatric surgery. Folate deficiency does not cause the dorsal column and lateral column neurological deficits described in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune destruction of pancreatic beta cells\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism behind type 1 diabetes mellitus. While diabetes can cause peripheral neuropathy, it does not explain the macrocytic anaemia or the pattern of neurological deficits seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcessive alcohol consumption\u003C/strong\u003E can result in direct neuropathy as well as B12 deficiency. This patient\u0027s alcohol consumption is unlikely to result in these symptoms unless there has been an unstated history of heavier drinking. In this case, the risk factor of his bariatric surgery is more likely to be relevant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIodine deficiency causing thyroid dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially explain the fatigue and neck swelling. However, this patient does not have any other relevant symptoms and this mechanism does not account for the neurological symptoms or the macrocytic anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitamin B12 deficiency can occur after bariatric surgery is due to impaired absorption from loss of intrinsic factor and altered gastrointestinal anatomy.","Subacute combined degeneration of the spinal cord is a neurological complication of vitamin B12 deficiency, affecting the dorsal and lateral columns.","Macrocytic anaemia with neurological deficits should prompt consideration of vitamin B12 deficiency, especially in people with risk factors for malabsorption."],"references":["Ankar A, Kumar A. Vitamin B12 Deficiency. [Updated 2022 Oct 22]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-.","Majumder S, Soriano J, Louie Cruz A, Dasanu CA. Vitamin B12 deficiency in patients undergoing bariatric surgery: preventive strategies and key recommendations. Surg Obes Relat Dis. 2013 Nov-Dec;9(6):1013-9. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24091055/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83972"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1437"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83972"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-02T14:21:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T14:23:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1437"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101533"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","